Samsung Solve for Tomorrow 2026 — Sports Category
This document establishes the exact, bulletproof technical foundation for the Vocal Willow MVP prototype.
One critical reframe dictates your engineering decisions for the Samsung India jury: The bat already knows what happened — you just have to read it and speak it honestly. When a bat strikes a ball, a violent acoustic "tock" registers on the microphone alongside a distinct rotational profile in the gyroscope. A swing through empty air will have the motion but completely lacks the impact sound. By combining motion detection with directional acoustics, hit vs. miss classification becomes highly accurate using affordable hardware.
The MVP Scope (Blind Cricket Focus)
The primary goal of the Vocal Willow MVP is to enable a blind cricketer to step into a net and practice completely independently, with zero sighted assistance.
Concretely, the v1 MVP is:
The Handle Node: A lightweight, 3D-printed enclosure mounted securely to the top of a cricket bat handle containing the full sensor loop.
The Audio App: A local mobile application that communicates with the bat via Web Bluetooth. The instant contact or a miss is registered, it triggers a pre-recorded audio file ("Missed," "Clean Hit").
The Local Log: A visual and auditory session tracker that records balls faced, hits, misses, and hit percentage, culminating in a localized spoken summary: "You hit 14 of 20 balls. That's 70 percent."


What to Deliberately NOT Build in v1:
To prevent overclaiming, scope creep, or fatal jury traps during engineering reviews, the following features are strictly excluded from the initial prototype:
Multi-Sport Integration (Paddleball/Pickleball): While the broader vision accommodates court sports, v1 is locked exclusively to Blind Cricket to ensure bulletproof accuracy before scaling.
Live Text-to-Speech (TTS): Native TTS engines inject lag. The MVP relies solely on static, pre-recorded audio clips to achieve an instantaneous response under 200 ms.
Complex Machine Learning (ML): Do not use ML on raw sensor traces. Simple, explainable threshold logic handles detection. It is vastly faster to debug and easy to justify mathematically to a technical juror.
External Ball Tracking: The device does not estimate ball distance or speed, as a standalone bat sensor cannot measure spatial properties of an un-tracked ball.
Hardware Architecture & Bill of Materials (BOM)
The hardware stack utilizes highly standard, accessible components sourced locally in India (e.g., SP Road, Lamington Road, Robu.in) to keep production costs near ~₹1,500.
Component Breakdown
Microcontroller: ESP32 DevKit Board. Acts as the core processor, managing sensor sampling and driving the Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) link.
Motion Tracking: MPU6050 Accelerometer/Gyroscope Module. Used primarily to detect the high-velocity angular rotational peak of a physical swing.
Acoustic Tracking: MAX9814 Electret Microphone Module. Provides automated gain control to isolate the high-frequency impact "tock" of the ball meeting willow.
Power Subsystem: A standard 3.7V Lithium-Polymer (LiPo) battery managed by a TP4056 charging module. A compact DC-DC step-up boost module steps the voltage up to a stable 5V rail required by the ESP32 and sensor components.
Enclosure: A robust, lightweight 3D-printed case designed for structural stability. It features a split-clamp architecture that fastens tightly over the top of the handle, ensuring the electronics do not slide or absorb destructive axial shock directly.
Dual-Threshold Detection Algorithm
The ESP32 runs a rule-based state machine that completely bypasses heavy processing by gating acoustic signals behind motion profiles.
