Optimization Notes
Gated Audio Capture: The app or ESP32 does not monitor ambient room volume. The microphone channel is asleep until the gyroscope registers a physical swing exceeding 380 deg/s. This eliminates false positives caused by cheering, shouting, or nearby players.
Cooldown Interlock: A 650 ms structural lockout follows every shot event. This filters out secondary echo signatures and prevents a player from double-triggering the system when they tap their bat against the ground post-swing.
App Integration & BLE Payload Layout
The ESP32 acts as a BLE server broadcasting over Web Bluetooth directly to an offline, audio-first frontend interface.
BLE Characteristics
Event Characteristic (SVC 8b9e0001): A strict notify-only channel. The payload uses a compressed JSON string designed for minimal transit overhead:

{"swing": 1, "hit": 1, "a": 5.2, "g": 420, "id": 3} 

* `hit`: Binary flag ($1$ = Hit, $0$ = Miss)[cite: 3]. * `a`: Dynamic G-force or acoustic amplitude registering contact quality[cite: 3]. * `g`: Peak gyroscope rotational velocity achieved during swing execution[cite: 3]. ### The Accessibility Loop The mobile app operates entirely offline and requires no login sequences or server handshakes[cite: 1]. Upon receiving a BLE notification, the phone instantly pulls the matched pre-recorded audio snippet from local storage and plays it[cite: 1, 3]. The user interface must be verified visually and audibly with native Android TalkBack active, ensuring large touch boundaries, high contrast, and spoken confirmation indicators for all battery and connection profiles[cite: 1]. 



